1.-LIFE AND METHOD OF LIVY.

'l'itus Livius was born at Patavium (Padua), whence he took his cognomen of Patavinus, between the years 59 and 57 ΒΑ). The exact date is uncertain. He was prob- ably of good family, to judge from the aristocratic tone of his writings, and from the fact that the O. Cornelius who took the auspiees before the battle of Pharsalia (48 nc.) was a relative of his. At Patavium, the populous and busy town of the Veneti in the eastern district of Trans-Padane Gaul, near the mouth of the Po, he probably learned to declaim in public, as was usual; but he early moved to Rome, where he spent much of his life, dying at his native place in 17 AJJ. at the age of about 75. His first books (L-X.) are supposed to have been published before 20 B.c., and from that date to his death he was unceasingly busy with his work. Hc was a friend of the Emperor Augustus, although himself one who regretted the Republic and applauded Caesar-’s murderers. He seems to have had nothing to do with politics, and was so enabled to devote all his time to the task before him. Augustus' accession closed the history of Republican Rome. Livy volunteered to systematise that history—the history of. 700 years. Livy is the first Latin historian, with the exception of Caesar, whose works have come down to us to any large extent.
